Pop your #kettle{} on to boil. Halve the @green pepper{1}(halved and seeded) and discard the core and seeds. Chop into small pieces. Trim the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced) and thinly slice. Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(halved and deseeded), deseed then finely chop. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the pepper, garlic, chilli and half the spring onion. Stir and cook for ~{2%minutes}, then add the @red thai style paste{35%g} and stir together.

> Tip: Add less chilli if you don't like spice!

After ~{1%minute}, pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml} and mix until smooth. Add the @chicken stock powder{1} with the @water{400%ml} from your kettle and bring to a simmer.

Add the @peanut butter{1%tbsp} and a @?sugar{pinch} to your pan. Simmer gently for ~{10%minutes}. Taste the laksa and add seasoning if you think it needs it - salt, pepper, sugar - whatever suits your taste!

Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chicken thigh{210%g} and lime zest. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Stir-fry until cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}. When cooked, remove to a #plate{} and cover with #foil{} to keep warm.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

When the laksa has been cooking for 10 mins, add in the @egg noodle nests{2}. Cook until soft enough to eat, about ~{4%minutes}.

> Tip: The noodles may soak up some of the coconutty liquid. If this is the case, just add a splash of water to get it back to a soupy consistency.

Add the chicken to the pan and simmer until the chicken is piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from the heat and add half the lime juice.

> Finish with a squeeze of lime.

Taste and add @salt{}, @pepper{} and more lime juice if you feel it needs it. Serve in big #bowls{} topped with the coriander and the remaining spring onion. Enjoy!